  "prompt": "Why does shaking a soda cause it to explode?",
  "response": "Shaking a soda can causes it to explode when opened due to the rapid release of carbon dioxide (CO2) gas that is dissolved in the liquid. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the process:\n\n1. **Carbonation**: Soda is carbonated by dissolving CO2 gas in it under high pressure. When the can is sealed, the pressure inside is higher than the atmospheric pressure outside, keeping the gas dissolved in the liquid.\n\n2. **Shaking**: When a soda can is shaken, the agitation causes bubbles of CO2 to form throughout the liquid. This process displaces the liquid and creates more nucleation sites (places where gas bubbles can form), leading to an increased number of gas bubbles.\n\n3. **Building Pressure**: As the bubbles form and expand, they aggregate and push against the liquid, creating more pressure inside the can. This pressure can exceed the structural limits of the can if shaken sufficiently.\n\n4. **Opening the Can**: When the tab of the can is pulled, the pressure inside the can is released almost instantaneously. The rapid drop in pressure allows the dissolved CO2 to come out of solution explosively, causing the gas to expand rapidly, which pushes the liquid out of the can forcefully.\n\n5. **Explosion Effect**: This results in the soda spraying out of the opening, which can look like an explosion. The more it was shaken, the more CO2 is released, and the more explosive the reaction becomes.\n\nTo summarize, shaking a soda increases the number of bubbles and the pressure of gas in the can. When opened, this pressure creates a rapid release of gas and liquid, resulting in an explosive effect.",
